{{French language}}{{IPA notice}} In [[French orthography|French spelling]], '''aspirated "h"''' ([[French language|French]]: ''"h" aspiré'') is an initial [[silent letter]] that represents a [[hiatus (linguistics)|hiatus]] at a [[word#Word boundaries|word boundary]], between the word's first [[vowel]] and the preceding word's last vowel. At the same time, the aspirated ''h'' stops the normal processes of [[contraction (grammar)|contraction]] and [[liaison (French)|liaison]] from occurring.<ref name=fagyal2006>{{cite book|last=Fagyal|first=Zsuzsanna|title=French: A Linguistic Introduction|year=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=0-521-52896-8|pages=65–66, 224, 275–276}}</ref>
The name of the now-silent ''h'' refers not to [[aspirated consonant|aspiration]] but to its former pronunciation as the [[voiceless glottal fricative]] [h] in [[Old French]] and in [[Middle French]].{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}
== List of French words which begin with an aspirated ''h''== {{copy to Wiktionary}} The following list contains only the dictionary head entries and not all the forms that can be derived from them. For example, it does not contain past participles or transitive verbs when used as adjectives or nouns. It does not include composite words unless the omission might cause confusion among homonyms distinguished only by diacritic signs.
* In all French words that begin with ''h'', the following letter is a vowel. * Most aspirated-''h'' words are derived from [[Germanic languages]].<ref name=fagyal2006 /> * The ''h'' is generally not aspirated in words of Latin and Greek origin.<ref name=southworth1970>{{cite journal|last=Southworth|first=Marie-José|title=French Words in H-|journal=The French Review|date=October 1970|volume=44|issue=1|pages=63–71|jstor=385928}}</ref> * None of the rare words with a ''y'' after an initial ''h'' has an aspirated ''h''. In addition, ''h'' is rarely aspirated before an ''i''. * Before other vowels, the ''h'' is often aspirated, except for those coming from the oldest [[Greek language|Greek]] roots. * The ''h'' is aspirated in [[onomatopoeia]]. * There are numerous exceptions, and etymology often cannot explain them satisfactorily.<ref name=southworth1970 />
In French dictionaries, words with an initial aspirated ''h'' are traditionally prefixed with an [[asterisk]] but with no effect on their alphabetical arrangement. The following list is compiled from the ''Dictionnaire du Trésor de la langue française'' and the ''Dictionnaire de l'Académie française''. It lacks many proper names and recent borrowings. In general, if a borrowed word is pronounced with an {{IPA|[h]}} in its language of origin, the ''h'' will be conserved in French orthography and be aspirated.
