{{Infobox book | name = The Te of Piglet | title_orig = | translator = | image = Tepig.jpg | caption = | author = [[Benjamin Hoff]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = English | series = | subject = Taoism, Philosophy | genre = | publisher = [[Dutton Penguin|Dutton Books]] | pub_date = 1992 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 257 | isbn = 0-525-93496-0 | dewey= 299/.514 20 | congress= PR6025.I65 Z69 1992 | oclc = 25413491 | preceded_by = [[The Tao of Pooh]] | followed_by = }}
'''''The Te of Piglet''''' is a 1992 philosophical non-fiction book written by [[Benjamin Hoff]] as a companion to his 1982 work ''[[The Tao of Pooh]]''.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/14/books/best-sellers-february-14-1993.html BEST SELLERS: February 14, 1993] ''New York Times''</ref> The book was published by [[Dutton Penguin|Dutton Books]] and spent 21 weeks on the ''Publishers Weekly'' Bestseller List and 37 weeks on the ''New York Times'' Bestseller List.<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-14-023016-1 The Te of Piglet] Publishers Weekly</ref><ref>[http://www.hawes.com/1993/1993-06-06.pdf BEST SELLERS: June 6, 1993] Hawes.com</ref>
==Synopsis== In ''The Te of Piglet'', the [[Piglet (Winnie-the-Pooh)|Piglet]] character of the ''[[Winnie-the-Pooh]]'' books explains the Chinese concept of ''[[De (Chinese)|Te]]'', meaning 'power' or 'virtue'.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1992/11/29/style/peace-is-a-bookshelf-away.html?src=pm Peace Is a Bookshelf Away] ''New York Times''</ref> Hoff elucidates the Taoist concept of 'Virtue — of the small'; though, he also uses it as an opportunity to elaborate on his introduction to [[Taoism]]. It is written with many embedded stories from the [[A. A. Milne]] Winnie the Pooh books, both for entertainment and because they serve as tools for explaining Taoism.
In the book Piglet is shown to possess great power — a common interpretation of the word Te, which more commonly means Virtue — not only because he is small, but also because he has a great heart or, to use a Taoist term, [[Three Treasures (Taoism)|Tz'u]]. The book goes through the other characters — [[Tigger]], [[Owl (Winnie-the-Pooh)|Owl]], [[Rabbit (Winnie-the-Pooh)|Rabbit]], [[Eeyore]] and [[Winnie-the-Pooh|Pooh]] — to show the various aspects of [[Human nature|humanity]] that Taoism says get in the way of living in harmony with the [[Tao]].
==Reception== The ''[[Palm Beach Post]]'' stated that although the first book was a "sleeper hit", the ''Te of Piglet'' "falls short as a companion to [the] Tao of Pooh".<ref>Smith, Peter. '' TE OF PIGLET FALLS SHORT AS COMPANION TO TAO OF POOH''. Palm Beach Post. November 15, 1992, p6L.</ref> Princeton University's [[Cotsen Children's Library]] praised the book.<ref>[http://www.princeton.edu/cotsen/pdfs/Te-Piglet-eileen.pdf Review: ''The Te of Piglet''] Cotsen Children's Library</ref> ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' wrote "if you like marshmallow laced with arsenic, it was worth the wait".<ref>[http://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/benjamin-hoff/the-te-of-piglet/ THE TE OF PIGLET] ''Kirkus Reviews''</ref> ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' wrote "Hoff's tired attacks on the "Negative News Media" and on "Eeyore Amazons" who "call themselves feminists but . . . don't like femininity" weaken his presentation, but on the whole, his Taoist manifesto distills ageless personal and political wisdom, relaying an ecological message we ignore at our peril."<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-525-93496-7 The Te of Piglet] ''Publishers Weekly''</ref>
